 THE number of COVID-19 cases in Africa is now over one million, according to the Africa Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (Africa CDC). The Africa CDC said on Friday in an update on the pandemic that COVID-19 cases stood at 1,007,366 on Friday afternoon. Also on Friday, India reported 24,000 new cases within 24 hours to take its total toll to two million. South Africa has over a half of the one million cases in the continent. Death toll related to COVID-19 in Africa rose from 21,617 on Thursday to 22,066 yesterday. Africa CDC also reported 690,436 COVID-19 patients have recovered across the continent so far. South Africa’s infection figures of 538,184 are the world’s fifth-highest after the US, Brazil, India and Russia. It is followed by Egypt, Nigeria, Algeria and Morocco, the agency said. Africa CDC also said eight countries have reported higher COVID-19 fatality rates compared to the global average. The countries are Chad, Sudan, Niger, Liberia, Egypt, Mali, Burkina Faso and Angola. South Africa, Djibouti, Sao Tome and Principe, Cape Verde and Gabon are reporting the most cumulative COVID-19 cases per 100,000 in Africa, Africa CDC added. India has registered 19,963 deaths from the virus, a much lower number than many other badly hit countries. India’s major cities have been worst hit by the pandemic. New Delhi and Mumbai each have about 100,000 cases, with 3,000 dead in the capital and nearly 5,000 in Mumbai. One high-profile victim of the global shutdown – the Taj Mahal – will remain closed, it was announced Sunday.